ng cynipids than might have been predicted. Competitive effects appear to be negligible, as the wasp attacks tissues on the two oak species that are not utilized by other cynipids in the U.K. The effect of adding an abundant new host on the dynamics of shared natural enemies was reduced because virtually all the parasitoids emerging from the sexual galls on Q. cerris were males, and the agamic galls were almost parasite-free.
